            <div class="Entry">
              <div class="Subject">
                <span id="Subject">Build scripts and Ruby</span>
              </div>
              <div class="Body">
                <div class="InlineGoogleAd"><script type="text/javascript"><!--
                google_ad_client = "pub-8264790134546506";
                google_ad_width = 250;
                google_ad_height = 250;
                google_ad_format = "250x250_as";
                google_ad_channel ="6417806153";
                google_color_border = "CCCCCC";
                google_color_bg = "FFFFFF";
                google_color_link = "000000";
                google_color_url = "666666";
                google_color_text = "333333";
                //--></script>
                <script type="text/javascript"
                  src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
                </script></div>
                <span id="Body"><p>I've been spending some time this week playing release engineer for our web applications. One thing that becomes more and more apparent as I automate more and more of our deployment process is how build scripts are really programs, and must be treated as such. XML-based tools like *Ant and MSBuild really don't cut it because you wind up going through rather severe context switches between the declarative nature of the targets and items, and some of the programmatic tasks such as generating environment-specific <code>web.config</code> files.

<p>I prefer to be able to package declarative stuff with imperative stuff in a single file, so that I can visualize my entire build process. Ruby lets me do this in ways that I never really quite expected.

<p>If you're itching to try a scripting language, consider using it to do things like build scripts or testing your "real" applications. You'll find it harder and harder to switch back to coding in the language that you used to create your "real" apps :)</span>
              </div>
              <div class="ByLine">
                By
                <span id="Author" class="Author">John</span>
                Created on:
                <span id="DateCreated" class="DateCreated">5/5/2005 9:40:53 PM</span>
                modified on:
                <span id="DateModified" class="DateModified">5/5/2005 9:47:05 PM</span>
              </div>
              <h2>Others comments:</h2>
              <div class="Comments">
                
                    <div class="Comment">
                      <span id="CommentsRepeater__ctl0_CommentBody">Paul - right now it's a roll-my-own system hybrid system. That's mostly due to a non-trivial set of NAnt scripts that work and build the system as it stands today. Eventually I think the NAnt scripts will be rolled into Rake to simplify future maintenance of the build system.

Thanks for the pointer to Fowler's blog entry. I dimly recall reading that, although I had incorrectly attributed it to Bruce Eckel in conversations around the office :)</span>
                      <div class="CommentByLine">
                        By
                        <span id="CommentsRepeater__ctl0_Label1" class="Author">John Lam</span>
                        on:
                        <span id="CommentsRepeater__ctl0_Label2" class="DateCreated">5/6/2005 9:11:35 AM</span>
                      </div>
                    </div>
                  
                    <div class="Comment">
                      <span id="CommentsRepeater__ctl1_CommentBody">I couldn't agree more.

I've done just the same for my "pet" project (http://blogs.geekdojo.net/pdbartlett/articles/WhatbiHome.aspx) and have been so impressed by Ruby that I've even ported a simplified version of the main project to it.

Martin Fowler has also said much the same (http://www.martinfowler.com/bliki/BuildLanguage.html), not that your recommendation doesn't carry enough weight in its own right, of course!

Just out of interest, are you using rake or a "home-grown" system?</span>
